@NODE reqments "System Requirements"

  @{b}System requirements@{ub}

  This package requires Directory Opus 4.x. It was not tested with any
  older versions, but it MAY work (DirOpus 4 is free, so: UPGRADE !)

  Some of the programs require 'rexxsupport.library'. This library is
  distributed with AmigaOS and should be installed already.

  All programs in this distribution are written in ARexx, so your
  ARexx-Server must be active. You can achieve this by adding the line:

     C:RUN >NIL: SYS:System/Rexxmast

  to your User-Startup. This will activate RexxMast after the next reboot.
  To activate RexxMast immediately, just Double-Click on its icon, which
  can be found in the 'SYS:System/' drawer

  If a program or script has further requirements, it will be mentioned in
  its description.

@ENDNODE

@NODE install "Installation

  @{b}Installation@{ub}

  DOpus 4 Plus consists of a lot of single ARexx scripts. Just copy all
  of them (or just the ones you intend to use) to any place on your
  HardDisk (DOpus:Rexx/ is recommended).

  The configuration of each of these scripts is described in the @{" Usage " link usage}
  section. Normally you just have to define a new button or menu item.

  In the 'C' drawer of this distribution you will find two small CLI tools
  for comparing files. Have a look at their documentation for further
  informations.

@ENDNODE

@NODE usage "Usage"

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  DOpus 4 Plus consists of a lot of single programs. These programs, their
  configuration and usage are described below.

  @{b}Scripts that extend DirOpus' functionality@{ub}

     @{" CleanRAMDisk   " link CleanRAMDisk}

        Deletes all crap files from RAM: but keeps the system files
        (Clipboards, ENV, T, disk.info).

     @{" CompareNames    " link CompareNames}

        Compares the names of the files in the two directory listers and
        selects the files that differ.

     @{" CompareWin     " link CompareWin}

        Compares the names/comments/protection bits/sizes of the files in
        the two directory listers and selects the files that differ.

     @{" HideFiles      " link HideFiles}

        Hides files (in other words: removes them from the display) that
        match a given pattern (or that DON'T match that pattern).

     @{" HuntComment    " link HuntComment}

        Works like DOpus' internal 'Hunt' function, but hunts for file
        comments.

     @{" Killdir        " link KillDir}

        Deletes blocked directories (removes all Assigns pointing to the
        directory, closes WB drawers showing the directory...).

     @{" PatternOpus    " link PatternOpus}

        Rename/Copy/Move lots of files to a numbered sequence by giving
        a name pattern and a starting number.

     @{" SelectAddOn    " link SelectAddOn}

        Select files by size or comment.

     @{" SelectSameName " link SelectSameName}

        Select files with same name, optionally compare the files.

     @{" SelectSameSize " link SelectSameSize}

        Select files with same size, optionally compare the files
        (can operate on both directory listers or only on the active one).

     @{" SequenceSelect " link SequenceSelect}

        Select numbered file sequences easily.

     @{" SortByComment  " link SortByComment}

        Copies/moves files into subdirectories whose name match the file
        comment.

     @{" TwoFiles       " link TwoFiles}

        Call an external program with the two selected files as an argument
        (the two files may be spread across both directory listers).

     @{" VCopy          " link VCopy}

        Comfortable Version Copy.

     @{" WinVersion     " link WinVersion}

        Opens a DOpus requester showing version information on selected
        file(s).

  @{b}Scripts that integrate DirOpus and Workbench 3.5+@{ub}

     @{" OpenWBDrawer   " link OpenWBDrawer}

        Opens the active directory lister on Workbench.

     @{" UpdateWBDrawer " link UpdateWBDrawer}

        Updates a Workbench drawer if the appropriate DOpus lister has
        changed.

     @{" WB2DOpus       " link WB2DOpus}

        Use DOpus' internal functions (Hunt, Search, Comment etc.) from
        Workbench.

  @{b}Scripts that integrate DirOpus with other software@{ub}

     @{" Attach2Mail    " link attach2mail}

        Starts YAM (if it ain't running) opens a new mail window and
        attaches all selected files to it.

@ENDNODE

@NODE CleanRAMDisk

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  This script deletes all files and directories in the RamDisk except the
  directories 'Clipboards', 'ENV' and 'T' aswell as the file 'Disk.info'.

  May be useful if a lot of 'crap' files accumulated in the RamDisk.

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/CleanRAMDisk.dopus

  That's all. No flags etc. needed.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Start the script whenever you want to get rid of all non-system files in
  the RamDisk. If one of the DirOpus directory windows shows the content
  of a directory that is erased by the operation, it will show RAM:
  afterwards.

  @{b}History@{ub}

  v2.0: - Removed the rexxsupport library calls (rexxsupport.library
          isn't required anymore)
        - General clean up of the 'source code' :)

  v1.0: - Initial public release

  @{b}Authors@{ub}

  Philippe Ferrucci / Christoph Gutjahr

@ENDNODE

@NODE CompareNames

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  Compares the names of the files in the two directory listers and selects
  all files that have no matching entry in the destination directory window.

  See also: 

     @{" CompareWin   " link CompareWin}

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/CompareNames.dopus

  That's all. No flags etc. needed.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Just start the script. It will compare the two directory windows and
  highlight all files in the source window that have no matching entry in
  the destination window.

  You can abort the script at any time by pressing both mouse buttons.

  @{b}History@{ub}

  v2.0:  - Rewrote the script to gain speed.
         - Removed one possible crash cause (DirOpus's ARexx port is still
           buggy...)

  v1.02: - Initial public release (written by Miloslaw Smyk), called
           'CompareDirs'.

  @{b}Authors@{ub}

  Christoph Gutjahr / Miloslaw Smyk

@ENDNODE

@NODE CompareWin

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  Compares the names/sizes/comments/protection bits of the files in the two
  directory listers and selects all files that have no matching entry in the
  destination directory window.

  See also:

     @{" CompareNames " link CompareNames}

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/CompareWin.dopus

  That's all. No flags etc. needed.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Just start the script. It will compare the two directory windows and
  highlight all files in the source window that have no matching entry in
  the destination window.

  You can abort the script at any time by pressing both mouse buttons.

  NOTE: 'matching entry' means that both files have the same size, comment,
        protection bits and name!

  NOTE: The routine that compares names/comments is NOT case sensitive.

  @{b}History@{ub}

  v1.1: - Initial public release

  @{b}Author@{ub}

  OPI

@ENDNODE

@NODE HideFiles

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  This script will hide files (in other words: remove them from the
  display) that

     a) match a given pattern
  or

     b) don't match that given pattern

  That sounds strange to you ? It works just like selecting files that
  match a pattern, just that the files won't be selected, they will be
  hidden!

  The files do not get deleted of course, if you want to see them again,
  just RESCAN the directory (right-click on the tiny 'R' button in the
  center of DirOpus' window).

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/HideFiles.dopus [SHOW]

  That's all. No flags etc. needed.

     - SHOW : Normally files that match the given pattern will be hidden.
              Specify this argument, and the files that DON'T match
              the given pattern will be hidden.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Just start the script. A requester will appear, asking for a select
  pattern (you can use all Wildcards DirOpus normally accepts, i.e. '?'
  or '*').

  Now all files will be hidden that match/don't match the given pattern.

  The hidden files can't be accessed from within DirOpus until you
  RESCAN the directory contents.
  
  @{b}History@{ub}

  v1.0: - Initial public release

  @{b}Author@{ub}

  Christoph Gutjahr

@ENDNODE

@NODE HuntComment

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}
 
  Works like DirOpus' internal 'Hunt' command, but will search for matching
  file comments instead of matching file names. Selected directories will
  be scanned recursively.

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/HuntComment.dopus

  That's all. No flags etc. needed.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Just use this like the internal 'Hunt' command: Select a few directories
  and/or files (selected directories will be scanned recursively) and start
  this script.

  A string requester will pop up, asking for a search string. Enter the
  string you want to search for and hit Okay. If you enter an empty search
  string, the script will find files WITHOUT a file comment.

  If a file comment is found, that matches the search string, a requester
  will appear, giving you the following choices:

     - Okay      : Scan this dir into the lister and mark ALL files whose
                   comment matches the search string

     - Skip File : Skip this file, continue searching

     - Skip Dir  : Skip this dir (this will not just skip the directory
                   where the current match was found, but all sub-
                   directories of this tree!)

     - Abort     : Abort the script

  NOTE: There are NO wildcards supported, the script will just find any file
        comment that contains the given search string! It will also ignore
        upper-/ lowercase!

  NOTE: This script will ignore the comments of directories!

  NOTE: Make sure that your directory names obey AmigaDOS rules (forbidden
        chars are ? # ~ % ' [ ] ( | ) * ` for example), otherwise weird
        things may happen...

  NOTE: This script won't work with the device list (unlike the original
        'SEARCH' and 'HUNT' functions).

  @{b}History@{ub}

  v2.6: - Initial public release

  @{b}Author@{ub}

  OPI

@ENDNODE

@NODE KillDir

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}
 
  Sometimes DirOpus refuses to delete a directory. This can have many
  reasons:

     - An assign points to the directory (or one of its subdirectories)

     - A Workbench drawer shows the content of this directory (or of one
       of its subdirectories)

     - The directory contains one or more files that are 'locked' by other
       applications

     - MUI applications also tend to block directories

     - ....

  KillDir tries to remove all assigns to a directory (and its
  subdirectories) and closes all Workbench drawers that show the directory
  or its subdirectories (REQUIRES AmigaOS 3.5!) and afterwards tries to
  delete the directory.

  This won't help in ALL cases, but you should be able to delete most of the
  locked directories with KillDir.

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/KillDir.dopus [WB] [DELETE]

  That's all. No flags etc. needed.

     [WB]     - Workbench drawers showing the directory will be closed ONLY
                if this argument is specified. This function is turned off
                by default, because it REQUIRES AmigaOS 3.5.

     [DELETE] - If this argument is specified, the directory will be
                deleted without confirmation. Otherwise a requester will
                appear and ask for confirmation.

  Both arguments are optional.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Select the directory that DirOpus refuses to delete and start the script.
  In many cases, the script will manage to delete the directory (but not in
  all cases!)

  If you did not specify DELETE as an argument, a requester will appear
  before anything gets deleted.

  @{b}History@{ub}

  v1.0: - Initial public release

  @{b}Author@{ub}

  Christoph Gutjahr

@ENDNODE

@NODE PatternOpus

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  PatternOpus is an ARexx scripts that renames, copies or moves lots of
  files to a numbered file sequence in one go. You just have to give it
  a name pattern (i.e. "frame?.jpg") and a starting number (i.e. "1").

  Output for the above example would be:

   frame1.jpg
   frame2.jpg
   frame3.jpg
   .....

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/PatternOpus.dopus [argument]

  [Argument] is optional and should be one of the following:

     - RENAME (default): renames files to a given pattern
   
     - COPY: Copies files to the destination directory and renames them
             to the given pattern (like DOpus' internal function 'CopyAs')
           
     - MOVE: Moves files to the destination directory and renames them
             to the given pattern (like DOpus' internal function 'MoveAs')

  That's all. No flags etc. needed.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Select a bunch of files you want to copy/move/rename and start the
  script.

  A requester will pop up, asking you for a name pattern. A name pattern
  MUST contain a question mark ("frame?.jpg" is a valid name pattern for
  example), which will later be replaced by numbers to distinguish between
  files.

  If the name pattern contains more than one question mark (i.e.
  "frame???.jpg), the inserted numbers will be 'stretched' to fit the
  number of question marks (i.e. "frame001.jpg" "frame002.jpg" etc.).

  A second requester will ask you for the starting number, then the
  renaming/copying/moving will be started.

  @{b}History@{ub}

  v2.0: - Just one script now which takes arguments
        - Minor bug (filenames with spaces weren't processed properly)
          fixed

  v1.0: - Initial public release. Three scripts, one for each purpose

  @{b}Author@{ub}

  Christoph Gutjahr

@ENDNODE

@NODE SelectAddOn

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  This script will give you two new pattern selection methods in Directory
  Opus 4:

     - Select by comment (select files whose comments match a given string
       pattern)

     - Select by size (select files that match a given size (or size range)

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/SequenceSelect.dopus [COMMENT]/[SIZE]

  That's all. No flags etc. needed.

     [COMMENT] - Select files by comment

     [SIZE]    - Select files by size

  If you specify no arguments (or both at the same time), a requester will
  pop up, asking for the sort method.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  NOTE: You can abort the process any time by pressing both mouse buttons.

  - Select by comment -

  Just enter a string. The script will highlight all files whose comments
  contain the string. Wildcards are NOT supported (that would have resulted
  in a major slowdown).

  - Select by size -

  Enter the exact size (will highlight all files with that size) or a size
  range:

     a) size1-size2: Selects all files bigger than size1 (or as big as
                     size1) and smaller than size2 (or as big as size2)

     b) size-      : Selects all files bigger than size (or as big as size)

     c) -size      : Selects all files smaller than size (or as big as
                     size)

  You can use '>' instead of '-', as in DOpus' internal Requester. But '>'
  doesn't mean 'greater than', it simply indicates a size range!

  @{b}History@{ub}

  v1.0: - Initial public release

  @{b}Author@{ub}

  Christoph Gutjahr

@ENDNODE

@NODE SelectSameName

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  NOTE: This script requires rmh.library ('Rexx Must Have' library) !!
 
  This script will select all files whose name appear in both directory
  listers. Optionally, it can compare those files to check if they are
  identical (an external program is required for that task).

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/SelectSameName.dopus [COMMAND] [ARGUMENTS]

  That's all. No flags etc. needed.

     [COMMAND]   - This should be the name of a CLI-tool that compares two
                   files to check if they are identical. By default, the
                   script will just search for files that have the same
                   name. If this argument is specified, the script will
                   utilize the specified CLI-tool to compare the files.
                   In this case, only identical files will be selected.

     [ARGUMENTS] - Arguments for the compare tool specified with COMMAND.

  NOTE:

  If you want to COMPARE files, you need a compare tool that sets the
  return code to '0' if both files are identical. The 'C' drawer of this
  distribution contains a CLI-tool called 'fcmp'. This program is small,
  fast and will do the job. It will compare files byte per byte.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Start the script and all files whose name appear in both listers will be
  selected. If you specified a compare program as an argument, only
  identical files will be selected.

  @{b}History@{ub}

  24.09.00 - better argument parsing
           - uses rmh.library now

  23.09.00 - Window activation fixed

  08.04.00 - Complete rework

  08.12.96 - QQUICK -> QUICK for new Cmp command

  13.11.95 - C:cmp supporting spaces in path

  20.05.95 - Completely rewritten

  17.04.95 - 'address' removed

  @{b}Author@{ub}

  Bert Jahn

@ENDNODE

@NODE SelectSameSize

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  NOTE: This script requires rmh.library ('Rexx Must Have' library) !!
 
  This script will select all files that have the same size as at least one
  other file. It can operate on both listers or just on the active one.
  Optionally, it can select only files that are identical to at least one
  other file (an external program is required for that task).

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/SelectSameSize.dopus [ONEWIN] [COMMAND] [ARGUMENTS]

  That's all. No flags etc. needed.

     [ONEWIN]    - If you specify this argument, only the files in the
                   active directory lister will be examined. By default,
                   the program will compare the files in both listers.

     [COMMAND]   - This should be the name of a CLI-tool that compares two
                   files to check if they are identical. By default, the
                   script will just search for files that have the same
                   size. If this argument is specified, the script will
                   utilize the specified CLI-tool to compare the files.
                   In this case, only identical files will be selected.

     [ARGUMENTS] - Arguments for the compare tool specified with COMMAND.

  NOTE:

  If you want to COMPARE files, you need a compare tool that sets the
  return code to '0' if both files are identical. The 'C' drawer of this
  distribution contains a CLI-tool called 'fcmp'. This program is small,
  fast and will do the job. It will compare files byte per byte.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Example 1:

  You want to examine both directory listers and select all files that
  have a matching entry (=same filesize) in the opposite window:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/SelectSameSize.dopus

  Example 2:

  You want to examine both directory listers and select all files that
  have an IDENTICAL entry in the opposite window:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/SelectSameSize.dopus DOpus:C/fcmp

  Example 3:

  You want to examine just the active directory lister and select all
  files that are identical:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/SelectSameSize.dopus ONEWIN DOpus:C/fcmp

  @{b}History@{ub}

  24.09.00 - SelectSameSizeOneWin.dopus added
           - better argument parsing
           - uses rmh.library now

  23.09.00 - Window activation fixed
           - Bug in selection fixed

  08.04.00 - Complete rework

  08.12.96 - QQUICK -> QUICK for new Cmp command

  13.11.95 - C:cmp supporting spaces in path

  28.05.95 - Optimize

  19.05.95 - Initial

  @{b}Author@{ub}

  Bert Jahn

@ENDNODE

@NODE SequenceSelect

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  This script lets you select numbered file sequences (i.e. frame01.iff,
  frame02.iff, frame03.iff...) easily. Just select one file of the sequence
  and start this  script.

  You can select several file sequences at once (just select one file out
  of each sequence and start this script).
 
  It works with all NUMBERED sequences, i.e.:

     - frame01.jpg, frame02.jpg, frame03.jpg...
     - 01.iff, 02.iff, 03.iff...
     - 0001.iff, 0002.iff, 0003.iff...
     - pic01, pic02, pic03...

  This script will even work if the filename contains only numbers (i.e.
  0001, 0002, 0003...), but in this case it will just select all files with
  the same filename length as the file selected by the user - so beware!

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/SequenceSelect.dopus

  That's all. No flags etc. needed.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Select a file of the sequence you want to select (or several files out of
  several sequences) and start the script. That's all!

  Note: If other files (that do not belong to a sequence) are selected,
  they won't be affected.

  @{b}History@{ub}

  v1.1: - Bugfix (filenames that contained spaces weren't processed
          correctly)

  v1.0: - Initial public release

  @{b}Author@{ub}

  Christoph Gutjahr

@ENDNODE

@NODE SortByComment

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  If you use an Amiga Web browser to download a file from the internet, the
  browser will put the URL where the file was downloaded from into the
  file's comment string.

  SortByComment will copy/move all selected files into subdirectories whose
  name match the file comment.

  It's a bit hard to explain, so here's an example: You have downloaded the
  file 'biz/dopus/dopus415jr.lha' from Aminet. The file comment will look
  like this: 'http://de.aminet.net/pub/aminet/biz/dopus/dopus415jr.lha'.

  If you select that file and start SortByComment, the following directories
  will be created in the destination window (if they don't exist):

     de.aminet.net/pub/aminet/biz/dopus/

  and the file will be copied/moved into the directory '.../dopus/'.

  This may be useful if you download a lot of stuff from Aminet (or similar
  file archives) and want to archive the whole stuff easily.

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/SortByComment.dopus [COPY / MOVE]

  That's all. No flags etc. needed.

     [COPY / MOVE] - Specifies if the selected files should be copied or
                     moved to the destination drawer. If you omit this
                     argument, a requester will pop up and ask for the
                     desired action.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Select a bunch of files and/or directories and start the script. The
  needed directories will be created and the files will be copied/moved
  into them. Selected directories will be scanned recursively.

  NOTE: Files without a comment will be ignored.

  NOTE: The filename of the destination file will be the name that is
        mentioned in the file's comment, NOT the name it currently has !
        Exception: If the comment is longer than 78 chars, the original
        name of the file will be used.

  NOTE: Filenames will be truncated to 30 chars.

  NOTE: Directory names will be truncated to 25 chars.

  NOTE: Forbidden chars (i.e. '#') will be replaced by '_'

  NOTE: '?' and ':' will be replaced by '/' (in other words: an extra
        directory will be created).

  NOTE: Set the 'buffers per window' (ConfigOpus/System/Directories) to a
        high value. This will speed up the script and ALL skipped entries
        (even those hidden in nested subdirectories) will be selected
        afterwards.

  @{b}History@{ub}

  v2.2: - Initial public release

  @{b}Author@{ub}

  OPI

@ENDNODE

@NODE TwoFiles

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  NOTE: This script requires rmh.library ('Rexx Must Have' library) !!
 
  Calls a program with the two selected files as an argument. There may be
  one file selected in each window or two files in one window.

  The script expects the name of an external program as an argument and
  will invoke this program with the two selected files as an argument.

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX:    DOpus:Rexx/TwoFiles.dopus [COMMAND]
     AMIGADOS: Wait 1
     BATCH:    T:Twofiles.tmp

  That's all. No flags etc. needed.

     [COMMAND] - This is the name of the external program that will be
                 invoked by the script.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  The example below calls the program 'wcmp' (can be found in the 'C'
  drawer of this distribution) to compare the two selected files.
  Other programs may be useful too...

     AREXX:    DOpus:Rexx/TwoFiles.dopus wcmp
     AMIGADOS: Wait 1
     BATCH:    T:twofiles.tmp

  Select two files and start the script: The specified program will be
  started, no matter which directory lister(s) contain the selected files.

  NOTE: The script will abort if there aren't exactly two files selected.

  @{b}History@{ub}

  24.09.00 - better argument parsing
           - uses rmh.library now

  09.04.00 - created

  @{b}Author@{ub}

  Bert Jahn

@ENDNODE

@NODE VCopy

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  Works like DirOpus' internal 'Copy' command, but brings up a requester
  with version string informations if a file already exists in the
  destination window and both files contain a version string.

  This script requires 'rexxsupport.library', which should be installed
  by a proper AmigaOS installation.

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/VCopy.dopus [VERSION COMMAND]

  That's all. No flags etc. needed.

     [VERSION COMMAND] - This is an optional argument. If you are NOT
                         using AmigaOS' standard 'Version' command, you
                         can specify with this argument, which command
                         should be used instead, an example would be:

                            DOpus:Rexx/VCopy.dopus DOVER

                         Beware: The replacement command must have the
                         same output as the original 'Version' command,
                         and it must be able to understand the arguments
                         FILE and FULL !
                         

  You can use this as a complete replacement for DOpus internal 'Copy'
  command, but this may result in MAJOR slowdowns (depends on the number of
  files you want to copy, and on their size) and is therefore not
  recommended.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Just use this like the internal commands: Select the files you want to
  copy and start the script.

  It will scan the destination drawer. If it finds duplicate files with
  version string information, a requester will pop up, showing you both
  version  strings. You have to decide if you want to keep the original
  file or overwrite it. If you want to overwrite it, it gets deleted.

  When the script is finished (or gets aborted), all files that were not
  copied (yet) remain selected.

  @{b}History@{ub}

  v3.0: - Initial public release (based on several other VersionCopy
          solutions I found/recieved, that's why it starts with v3)

  @{b}Authors@{ub}

  Christoph Gutjahr / Philippe Ferrucci

@ENDNODE

@NODE WinVersion

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  This will show version information of selected files in a standard
  Directory Opus requester.

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/WinVersion.dopus

  That's all. No flags etc. needed.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Just select some files and start the script. A requester will appear,
  showing you the version information of the first file (if this file
  has a version string, otherwise you'll be informed that no version
  string could be found).

  The requester has to buttons:

     - Next  : Show version information of next selected file
     
     - Abort : Aborts the script.

  @{b}History@{ub}

  v1.0: - Initial public release

  @{b}Author@{ub}

  Christoph Gutjahr

@ENDNODE

@NODE OpenWBDrawer

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  NOTE: This script requires AmigaOS 3.5 !!
 
  Opens DirOpus' currently active directory lister as a drawer on
  Workbench and (optionally) selects all files that were selected in the
  DirOpus window.

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/OpenWBDrawer.dopus [SELECT] [ICONONLY]

  If your DirOpus is not running on the Workbench screen, you HAVE to
  configure the action like this instead:

     AMIGADOS: SYS:Rexxc/rx DOpus:Rexx/OpenWBDrawer.dopus {Qp} [SELECT]...

  and check the 'WB to front' flag. The Argument {Qp} is absolutely
  neccessary and must be the FIRST argument (it's the name of DirOpus'
  ARexx message port) !

     [SELECT]   - If this argument is specified, the script will highlight
                  all files in the Workbench drawer, that were selected in
                  the DirOpus directory window.

     [ICONONLY] - If you specify SELECT and some of the files selected in
                  the DirOpus directory window don't have an icon attached,
                  the script will turn the mode of the WB drawer to 'Show
                  All Files'. You can prevent this by specifying ICONONLY.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Just start the script (with the Button/Menu Item/Hotkey you configured
  above) and the currently active dirctory lister will be opened as a
  Workbench window.

  @{b}History@{ub}

  v2.0: - Added the SELECT and ICONONLY options
        - Made the script work for people that don't have DirOpus running
          on Workbench screen

  v1.0: - Initial public release

  @{b}Author@{ub}

  Christoph Gutjahr

@ENDNODE

@NODE UpdateWBDrawer

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  NOTE: This script requires AmigaOS 3.5 !!
 
  This script will update any Workbench drawer that displays one of
  DirOpus' listers after the lister has changed.

  I.e. if you MOVEd some files within DirOpus, all Workbench drawers
  displaying DirOpus' source or destination lister will be updated.

  DirOpus doesn't give us the possibility to call a script if a directory
  has changed, so configuring this script requires a bit of work :(

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  The script must be started like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/UpdateWBDrawer.dopus [SOURCE] [DEST]

     [SOURCE] - Will update all Workbench drawers that display DirOpus'
                source lister

     [DEST]   - Will update all Workbench drawers that display DirOpus'
                destination lister

  The arguments are optional, if you specify no arguments, nothing will
  happen.

  Now think after which functions you want the Workbench drawers to be
  updated. You have to change the configuration of all buttons, menu items
  and hotkeys which should update WB drawers automatically.

  For example, if you want to update WB drawers after COPY and MOVE, the
  configuration of your COPY and MOVE Buttons have to be changed like that:

     The COPY button should look like this (COPY modifies only the
     destination directory):

        COMMAND: COPY
        AREXX:   DOpus:Rexx/UpdateWBDrawer.dopus DEST

     The MOVE button should look like this (MOVE modifies both source
     and destination directory):

        COMMAND: MOVE
        AREXX:   DOpus:Rexx/UpdateWBDrawer.dopus SOURCE DEST

  Quit a bit of work, I know. But if somebody really needs that feature,
  this is the only solution..

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Not much to say, as everything should work automatically if you
  configured it properly. Perhaps you may notice a small slowdown (depends
  on your machine, but I doubt that someone still uses a MC68000)...

  @{b}History@{ub}

  v1.2: - Initial public release

  @{b}Author@{ub}

  Christoph Gutjahr

@ENDNODE

@NODE WB2DOpus

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  NOTE: This script requires AmigaOS 3.5 !

  This script will integrate Workbench 3.5 and DirOpus. It must be started
  from Workbench (see below). It will start DirOpus (or bring its screen to
  front) and load the currently active Workbench drawer into DirOpus'
  source lister. It will then select all files in the lister that were
  selected in the Workbench drawer (optionally) and invoke ANY internal
  DirOpus command on them (optionally) !

  This enables you to use DirOpus' internal commands ('Hunt', 'Search',
  'Comment' etc.) from Workbench !

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  The script MUST be started from Workbench. I strongly suggest that you
  use T.H.E. for that purpose (Aminet:util/wb/the.lha). 'Toolmanager' or
  a similar software that lets you add new entries to Workbench's 'Tools'
  menu should do the trick too.

  Just create a new menu item and let it call the script (T.H.E. users may
  also define a new hotkey):

     WB2DOpus.rexx [SELECT] [COMMAND]

     [SELECT]  - If this argument is specified, all files that were
                 highlighted in the Workbench drawer will be selected in
                 DirOpus too

     [COMMAND] - One of DirOpus' internal commands ('Hunt', 'Search',
                 'Comment' etc.) that will be invoked. This argument
                 will be ignored if SELECT is not specified.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Below are some examples how to make use of WB2DOpus:

     Start DirOpus and import the currently active Workbench drawer:

        WB2DOpus.rexx

     Start DirOpus, import the currently active Workbench drawer 
     and select all files that were selected in the Workbench drawer:

        WB2DOpus.rexx SELECT

     Use DirOpus' HUNT function from Workbench (just select a few drawers
     and start the script):

        WB2DOpus.rexx SELECT HUNT

  Just make sure that a Workbench drawer is active when you start the
  script. Otherwise it will abort with an error message (there's nothing
  I can do about that).

  @{b}History@{ub}

  v1.0: - Initial public release

  @{b}Author@{ub}

  Christoph Gutjahr

@ENDNODE

@NODE Attach2Mail

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

  This script starts YAM (if it's not running already), opens a new mail
  window and attaches all selected files to the mail.

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  Configure a Button or Menu item in DirOpus and give it an appropriate
  name. The corresponding action should be configured like this:

     AREXX: DOpus:Rexx/Attach2Mail.dopus

  That's all. No flags etc. needed.

  @{b}Usage@{ub}

  Select a bunch of files and start the script. YAM will be started (if
  it's not running already) and a new mail window will pop up, with all
  selected files attached.

  @{b}History@{ub}

  v1.2: - Bugfix (DOpus was blocked when no files were selected)

  v1.1: - Bugfix (didn't work with right directory lister)

  v1.0: - Initial public release

  @{b}Author@{ub}

  Christoph Gutjahr

@ENDNODE

